<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ops-tax-compliance">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>gtm-strategist</domain>
    <summary>US solopreneur compliance: quarterly estimated payments, record-keeping, year-end deductions, timely filing, and state nexus management.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>tax</tag>
      <tag>compliance</tag>
      <tag>quarterly-estimates</tag>
      <tag>record-keeping</tag>
      <tag>filing</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>ops</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Tax Compliance &amp; Filing</title>
    <summary>An operational checklist for US-based solopreneurs to stay penalty-free: compute quarterly estimated payments using the safe-harbor rule (100% of prior-year tax, 110% if AGI exceeds 150K), pay by the IRS quarterly due dates, maintain a structured record-keeping system, execute year-end deduction sweep (retirement contributions, Section 179, expense acceleration), and file on time or extend. Non-US jurisdictions require localization.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Underpayment penalties compound at the federal short-term rate and accrue quarterly; missing even one payment while also underpaying creates compounding liability. The safe-harbor rule eliminates the penalty risk entirely — the methodology's primary rule — without requiring accurate current-year income projections, which are hard for variable-income businesses.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>First profitable year as a solopreneur or LLC: setting up quarterly estimate cadence.</item>
        <item>Multi-state nexus surfaces (SaaS selling into CA/NY/WA, or physical goods crossing thresholds).</item>
        <item>Year-end planning when LLC profit clears the threshold for S-Corp election (approximately 80K SE income).</item>
        <item>International seller hitting EU/UK VAT thresholds or Stripe Tax onboarding.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Novel situations: equity comp, R&amp;D credits, multi-entity structures, ERC, audit defense — require a CPA.</item>
        <item>Determining nexus liability in previously unserved jurisdictions — LLM nexus reasoning is frequently wrong.</item>
        <item>When an IRS or state notice has already arrived — go directly to a tax professional.</item>
        <item>Real-time tax calculations on customer transactions — use Stripe Tax / Avalara / TaxJar APIs, not an LLM.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="quarterly-estimates-who-must-pay">
      <rule>
        <statement>Pay quarterly estimated taxes if you expect to owe 1,000 or more in federal income tax for the year. Most profitable solopreneurs meet this threshold by Q1 of their first profitable year.</statement>
        <rationale>The IRS assesses the underpayment penalty quarterly, not annually. Missing a payment and trying to compensate at year-end still incurs penalties for the missed quarters.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="quarterly-estimates-due-dates">
      <p>US federal quarterly deadlines: Q1 (Jan–Mar) due April 15; Q2 (Apr–May) due June 15; Q3 (Jun–Aug) due September 15; Q4 (Sep–Dec) due January 15 of the following year. Note: April 15 covers both Q1 estimate and the prior-year tax return filing.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Set calendar reminders 2 weeks before each quarterly due date. A missed due date incurs a penalty at the federal short-term interest rate, assessed daily, for that specific quarter's payment shortfall.</statement>
        <rationale>The penalty compounds for the duration of underpayment. A Q1 missed payment accrues a penalty for the full nine months until April 15 of the following year.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="safe-harbor-calculation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use the safe-harbor rule to eliminate underpayment risk: pay 100% of prior-year tax liability in equal quarterly installments (110% if prior-year AGI exceeded 150,000). This eliminates the underpayment penalty regardless of actual current-year income.</statement>
        <rationale>Variable-income businesses cannot reliably project current-year profit mid-year. The safe-harbor method decouples quarterly payments from unpredictable income, eliminating penalty risk at the cost of potentially overpaying — refunded at filing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>When AGI exceeded 150,000 in the prior year, use the 110% safe-harbor threshold, not 100%. Agents miss this nuance consistently and produce underpayment plans that still accrue penalties for high earners.</statement>
        <rationale>The IRS 110% rule for high earners (Pub 505) is a discrete threshold, not a gradual scale. Missing it results in a penalty for the full year.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Simple approach: set aside 25–30% of every payout into a dedicated tax savings sub-account. Transfer to estimated payments each quarter. This is the operationally simplest approach for early-stage irregular income.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="setup-checklist">
      <p>One-time setup: form business entity, open business bank account, create a separate tax savings account, set up bookkeeping system (QuickBooks, Wave, or Xero), set quarterly calendar reminders.</p>
      <p>Ongoing monthly: record all income, categorize expenses, keep receipts, calculate monthly profit, transfer 25–30% to tax savings.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="record-retention">
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep tax returns permanently. Keep receipts, bank statements, invoices, mileage logs, and asset depreciation records for 7 years. Use digital formats with two-location backup.</statement>
        <rationale>The IRS has 3 years to audit a return in normal circumstances, 6 years if income is understated by 25%+, and indefinitely for fraud. 7-year retention covers the 6-year window with a safety margin.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Folder structure: taxes/YEAR/receipts/, invoices/, bank-statements/, quarterly-estimates/, tax-return.pdf; taxes/permanent/entity-formation/, major-contracts/.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Reconcile books monthly, not annually. Year-end reconciliation is where deductions get lost. Convert receipts to PDF with a corresponding row in an expenses CSV or accounting file at capture time.</statement>
        <rationale>Memory-based reconciliation after 11 months misses deductions, produces misclassified expenses, and creates audit risk from inconsistent categorization patterns.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="penalties">
      <p>Penalty types: Underpayment (owing 1K+ at filing — variable rate compounding daily, avoided by safe-harbor), Late filing (5%/month up to 25% — avoided by filing or extending on time), Late payment (0.5%/month on unpaid tax — avoided by paying estimated taxes), Accuracy (20% of underpayment — avoided by documentation and CPA review).</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use the extension form (Form 4868) if you cannot file by April 15. Extensions extend the filing deadline to October 15 but do NOT extend the payment deadline — any taxes owed are still due April 15.</statement>
        <rationale>A common mistake: filing an extension and believing no payment is due. The late-payment penalty (0.5%/month) begins immediately after April 15 regardless of extension status.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="audit-red-flags">
      <p>Red flags to avoid from day one: claiming 100% home office deduction (claim actual use percentage only), large round-number deductions (use exact amounts from receipts), cash-heavy business without receipts, Schedule C losses for multiple consecutive years without documentation of profit motive, 100% business-use vehicle claim.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep personal and business finances completely separate from the first day: dedicated business checking account and business credit card. Commingled finances is the single largest audit risk for sole proprietors.</statement>
        <rationale>Commingled accounts make it impossible to distinguish personal from business expenses without reconstruction. Auditors treat commingled accounts as evidence of inadequate books, which shifts the burden of proof to the taxpayer.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="year-end-planning">
      <rule>
        <statement>Reassess S-Corp election each December once SE-eligible income exceeds approximately 80–100K. The election can save 5–15K in self-employment tax annually at that income level.</statement>
        <rationale>SE tax is 15.3% on net self-employment income. An S-Corp allows splitting income into salary (SE-taxable) and distributions (not SE-taxable), reducing the SE-taxable portion. The savings compound annually.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>December year-end checklist: review annual profit and calculate current tax liability, max out retirement contributions (Solo 401(k) or SEP-IRA reduce taxable income dollar-for-dollar), purchase qualified equipment under Section 179 (deduct full cost in current year), pay outstanding business expenses to accelerate deductions, consider deferring income to January if expecting a lower-income year next year, calculate Q4 estimate due January 15.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="state-tax-compliance">
      <rule>
        <statement>Determine nexus in each state where you have customers, employees, or business activity before exceeding sales thresholds. Selling SaaS into CA/NY/WA above 100K in revenue or 200 transactions in 12 months typically creates nexus and tax registration obligation.</statement>
        <rationale>States have aggressive nexus enforcement and can assess back taxes plus penalties and interest retroactively. Early registration costs a few hours; retroactive compliance costs a lawyer and months of reconciliation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Multi-state checklist: determine nexus in each state, register for state taxes where required, set up state quarterly estimates, track sales by state for reporting, file state returns separately from federal.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>For SaaS businesses, check whether marketplace facilitator status applies before registering for direct sales tax collection. If you sell through a platform that collects and remits on your behalf, direct registration may be unnecessary.</statement>
        <rationale>Marketplace facilitator treatment eliminates the compliance burden for sales made through covered platforms. Registering unnecessarily creates ongoing filing obligations without benefit.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs cite tax rules from prior years as current-year law.</description>
        <reason>Always require the agent to cite an IRS publication number and revision date. Standard deduction, mileage rate, HSA/401(k) limits change annually. Verify against IRS.gov before acting.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents produce confident-sounding state nexus conclusions for jurisdictions the business has never operated in.</description>
        <reason>State nexus rules vary on dozens of dimensions (economic nexus thresholds, affiliate nexus, click-through nexus). Agents flatten this to single-rule reasoning. Require a CPA for any new-state nexus determination.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent pastes full tax IDs, SSNs, EINs, or bank account numbers into prompts.</description>
        <reason>Any data in the prompt can appear in logs, context summaries, or API response metadata. Use a scrubber pipeline before any LLM call involving financial records.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent drafts a response to an IRS notice without mandatory CPA sign-off.</description>
        <reason>IRS-facing communications trigger formal processes. An incorrect response can waive defenses or create new liability. Agents should only prepare a facts-and-timeline summary for the human and CPA to review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/safe-harbor.py" purpose="Quarterly federal estimate calculator: safe-harbor vs. current-year, outputs higher of the two"/>
      <template path="templates/tax-calendar.md" purpose="US federal and state tax deadlines with action descriptions"/>
    </templates>
    <how-to>
      <p>When using this methodology with agents for tax compliance:</p>
      <step>Use Claude subagents to organize records, reconcile bookkeeping exports against bank statements, classify expenses, surface deduction candidates, and prepare a CPA handoff packet.</step>
      <step>Never let an agent file a return or commit to a tax position — the agent prepares; the human (and ideally a CPA) decides.</step>
      <step>Follow the pipeline: monthly bookkeeping reconciliation (agent) → category audit (agent) → quarterly estimate calc draft (agent) → CPA review (human) → year-end deduction sweep (agent) → filing (human + tax software).</step>
    </how-to>
    <see-also>
